review_blob: 50cl bottle.  Rather unremarkable, but it looked real nice in the glass.  Flavor fades away too quickly - drinkable, but nothing lingers to make it memorable.
660ml bottle.  Sampled this at a bar, but had to make do with their woefully inadequate plastic cups.  Rich, dark and pleasant.  Wish Id had a proper pint-glass.

50cl bottle.  Pours dark with a great looking head.  Somewhat thin taste that reminded me more of a black beer... perhaps Ive been drinking too many imperials lately and its made me expect so much more from stouts.

750ml bottle - trappist glass.

Very nice.  Just what I needed this evening.  Id elaborate, but I didnt share.
660ml bottle - trappist glass.  I really dont have anything good to say about this one... the only defense possible is that it was a bad bottle.

Bottle - don de dieu glass.  It an interesting one, for sure.  Poured out nicely, looks great.  Better than average nose and the initial taste is quite satisfying.  A little too cloying as I neared the bottom of the glass.

Bottled (dated Nov. 2006 on label) - snifter.  Jet black with a thick head that looks like chocolate mouse, but gradually diminishes.  The nose, to me, comes across more burnt than roasted.  Tastes of dark chocolate and darker coffee.
Bottle.  Slightly more character than Miller Genuine Draft - and in a clear bottle to boot.  A deliberately mediocre beer made to compete in the lowest-common denominator market.
Bottle - draught glass.  I dont think its changed all that much, but a lot of the appeal went away when they quit using the old-style stubby bottles for this one.

750ml bottle - chalice.  Poured out a somewhat bland, reddish-brown.  Nothing really jumping out at me.  I picked up several bottles to lock away in storage, and imagine it will get much better with age.

Bottle - flute.  Perhaps Im too enamoured with krieks and such that really wear their fruit flavours on their sleeves - this one doesnt quite do it for me.  I always find that it seems to taste a bit watery.
Draught - pint glass @ Bily Kun.  Of all the Ephemere varieties, this one is still my favourite.
Draught - weizen glass.  An interesting change, and not completely unwelcome, but it falls well short of being overwhelming.

beer_name: Dieu du Ciel Route des pices

review_blob: Bottle - pint glass.  Pours a wonderfully opaque black, with a deep brown head that rose nicely and refused to dissipate.  Comes on like a standard stout, then fades away leaving a pleasant raspberry taste.  Certainly not an every day beer, but its a nice way to finish the night.  I found it serviceable the first time I tried it, and found myself in the mood to give it a second go-round tonight.  Im glad I did.  I guess I just had to be in the mood for it.
beer_name: Multi-Brasses Stout  la Framboise et au Chocolat

review_blob: Draught - pint glass.  I had really high hopes for this one.  I quite enjoy Dunkelwiezens and theyre hard to come by in Quebec.  Unfortunately this one didnt quite satisfy.

Draught - tulip.  Aged 1.5 years.  On tap during the anniversary celebrations in Sept. 06.  I think it was possibly the best experience Ive ever had drinking beer.  The only thing stopping me from giving it a solid 5 is that I could, conceivably, have something better someday.

Draught - pint.  I havent had this one in quite a while, but the marriage of cherry tartness with the richness of coffee and chocolate brought me back just about every night it was on tap.  Heres to hoping they bring out a new batch soon.
Draught - pint glass.  Hits like a good stout, but fades in a wash of vanilla.  Friends who like stouts love this beer, as do friends who normally hate stouts.
Draught - pint glass.  I cant express how great it is that Dieu du Ciel is only two blocks from my place.  Not their best stout, but a very quality beer nonetheless.

Bottle - 2006 vintage - snifter.  Onyx-black body with a dark brown head the rose to the top of the glass, then quickly dropped down without disappearing completely.  Coffee and dark chocolate notes that fade quickly.  Good, but lacks the punch of a truly great imperial stout.

Bottle - Delirium Tremens tulip.  For years this was among my favourites, but I dont enjoy it as much as I used to.  Perhaps my palate has grown up, or perhaps they just dont make it like they used to.  Still quite solid and a staple in my cellar.
Bottle - served in Duvel tulip.  Solid head that diminishes slowly, nice lacing on the glass.  Slightly bitter, dry.  I find it quite thirst quenching.

One of my all-time favourites.  As a general rule I try to avoid bottles that are less than a year old.  I find they tend to have a weak taste and need at least three years to really mature.  Great red/brown colour, rich head and a marvelous taste.
Wow.  I was hoping for something in the same vein as Quelque Chose, but instead Im handed a drink that makes me think Unibroue is chasing down the wine cooler market.
Served in a tulip glass, this is easily one of the best beers I can recall tasting.  The alcohol content is entirely masked by the rich taste of this stout.  Phenomenal.  Highly recommended.

Served in a Chimay chalice.  Pours out dark with a lush head.  Initial impression is a playful, rich taste, but one that lingers pleasantly in the mouth.  A fine complement to the Chimay cheese - if you can find it.

Served in a trappist chalice, this beer poured out wonderfully - with a head that rose to the top of the glass.  The initial taste is bitter and dry - it becomes a bit sweeter as it fades, but it fades a bit too quickly.  Maybe its just the weather and I need stronger that lingers in the mouth a lot longer.
